    narrator "{i}The debt terminal is in the commissary. A row of screens against the wall, where workers can check their \"balance\" during meal breaks. Most people avoid them. Looking at the numbers doesn't change them. It just makes them harder to ignore.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna stands in front of one. The screen is grimy, cracked in one corner. Someone has scratched \"TRAP\" into the metal frame, then scratched it out, then scratched it again.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She presses her palm to the reader. The tag in her neck syncs. The numbers appear.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{b}WORKER 477 - DEBT STATUS{/b}\n{i}Previous Balance:{/i} 487,341 ticks\n{i}Overnight Adjustment:{/i} +17 ticks (dormitory audit, standard)\n{i}Current Balance:{/i} 487,358 ticks (debt)\n{i}Daily Accrual Rate:{/i} 0.015%% (compounding)\n{i}Yesterday's Interest:{/i} 72 ticks\n{i}Yesterday's Net Earnings:{/i} -17 ticks\n{i}Projected Clearance Date:{/i} N/A (insufficient progress trajectory)\n{i}Note:{/i} Balance has increased 2.4%% over the past 30 days. Consider productivity enhancement opportunities.{{/color}}"
    narrator "{i}N/A. Not applicable. The system has calculated that she will never pay it off. It's not hiding it. It's just noting it, like any other data point.{/i}"
    narrator "Projected clearance date: never. They put it right there. They tell us."
    narrator "{i}She stares at the numbers. Runs them in her head. The habit she can't break.{/i}"
    narrator "487,358 ticks. Plus seventeen overnight for \"dormitory audit.\" They charged me for sleeping. Interest at 0.015%% daily means... 73 ticks today. Tomorrow, 73.1. The day after, 73.2. It compounds. It always compounds."
    narrator "If I worked a perfect shift every day-never sick, never slow, never injured-I'd earn maybe 55 ticks net. But the interest is 73. I fall behind by 18 ticks per day. Per day. That's 540 per month. 6,480 per year."
    narrator "In ten years, I'll owe 65,000 more than I do now. In twenty years, 130,000. And that's if the rate doesn't change. If they don't add fees. If I don't get sick."
    narrator "The math doesn't allow escape. The math is the point."
    narrator "{i}A worker next to her is checking his own balance. His face is blank. He's seen the numbers before. They all have.{/i}"
    worker "{i}[[not looking at her]]{/i} How long for you?"
    avyanna "{i}[[not looking at him]]{/i} Doesn't matter."
    worker "{i}[[flat]]{/i} Eight years. That's how long I've been here. Started with twelve thousand. Now I'm at four hundred thousand."
    narrator "Eight years. He's been here as long as I have. And his debt grew by almost forty times."
    worker "They adjust the rate, you know. When you get close to zero-when you're almost out-they find something. An equipment fee. A safety violation. A health assessment charge. [[beat] My buddy got within two thousand once. Two thousand. Then they hit him with a \"routine audit adjustment.\" Sixteen thousand. Just like that."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna doesn't respond. There's nothing to say.{/i}"
    worker "{i}[[pushing away from the terminal]]{/i} Good luck, four-seven-seven. Not that it matters."
    narrator "{i}He walks away. The screen blinks. Her numbers are still there. Waiting.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}She thinks about Bram.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Fifty years. He's been here fifty years. He started when the mine was new, when it was still called something other than the Kennel. He's watched generations of workers come and go-mostly go.{/i}"
    narrator "How is he still alive? The gold-lung should have taken him decades ago. The debt should have crushed him. The math should have-"
    narrator "{i}She stops. Reconsiders.{/i}"
    narrator "Maybe the math is different for him. Maybe there's something he knows. Something the rest of us don't."
    narrator "Or maybe he's just lucky. Maybe luck is the only thing the system can't calculate."
    narrator "But luck runs out. Everyone's luck runs out eventually."
    narrator "{i}She presses her palm to the terminal again. The screen updates.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{i}Productivity Enhancement Opportunity Available{/i}\n{i}Voluntary overtime: +4 hours{/i}\n{i}Additional earnings: 200 ticks (before deductions){/i}\n{i}Air premium (overtime): 30 ticks{/i}\n{i}Equipment rental (overtime): 45 ticks{/i}\n{i}Net overtime earnings: 125 ticks{/i}\n{i}Note: Overtime shifts may impact recovery and future productivity. Health consequences are the responsibility of the worker.{/i}{{/color}}"
    narrator "One hundred twenty-five ticks. Four extra hours. I'd fall behind by only... negative 52 today instead of negative 73. That's still negative. Still sinking. Just slower."
    narrator "They're offering me the chance to work myself to death slightly less quickly."
    narrator "{i}She declines the overtime. The screen chirps. Friendly. Helpful.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{i}Productivity Enhancement Opportunity Declined{/i}\n{i}Note: Declining voluntary opportunities does not affect your standing. However, consistent non-participation may be noted in quarterly reviews.{/i}{{/color}}"
    narrator "May be noted. In quarterly reviews. Which affect shift assignments. Which affect earnings. Which affect-"
    narrator "Everything is connected. Everything is designed."
    narrator "{i}She walks away from the terminal. The numbers stay behind. But she can feel them, following her like a shadow she can't shake.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The hab stack is quiet during second shift. Most of the bunks are empty-workers at their stations, earning ticks, falling behind.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna should be resting. Conserving. But she can't stop moving. The numbers are too loud in her head.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She finds herself at Bunk 473. Empty. Cold. The bunk that was occupied yesterday, that is always occupied, that is now-{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She stops. Looks.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The sheets have been stripped. The mattress is bare. The lockbox is empty, door hanging open. Standard procedure.{/i}"
    narrator "Four-seven-three. The bunk Coil paused at this morning. The one with the cold sheets."
    narrator "Someone died. Someone didn't wake up. And the system has already processed them out of existence."
    narrator "{i}A worker passes behind her. Older. Thin. The kind of thin that comes from giving away food rations to someone who needed them more.{/i}"
    della "{i}[[seeing Avyanna look]]{/i} You knew him?"
    avyanna "{i}[[flat]]{/i} Not really."
    della "Bram. Fifty. Started coughing last month. [[beat] Burned bright, that one."
    narrator "Burned bright. Like it's a compliment. Like making fifty and still dying in your bunk is an achievement."
    avyanna "{i}[[quiet]]{/i} What does that mean?"
    della "{i}[[surprised]]{/i} What?"
    avyanna "{i}[[still looking at the empty bunk]]{/i} Burned bright. Everyone says it. What does it mean?"
    narrator "{i}Della is silent for a moment. Looking at Avyanna like she's said something strange. Something dangerous.{/i}"
    della "{i}[[careful]]{/i} It means he worked hard. Didn't complain. Gave everything he had."
    avyanna "{i}[[flat]]{/i} Until it killed him."
    della "{i}[[defensive now]]{/i} It's respect. It's-"
    avyanna "Bram was killed."
    narrator "{i}The words come out before she can stop them. Three words. Too loud in the quiet hab stack.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Della's face goes pale. They look around-checking for supervisors, for cameras, for anyone who might be listening. Avyanna's tag gives a small vibration against her neck. Acknowledgment. Logged.{/i}"
    narrator "Stupid. Stupid. What did I just-"
    della "{i}[[hissing]]{/i} You can't say things like that. You can't-"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna is already walking away. Her hands are cold. Her heart is too fast. The tag is warm against her neck, warmer than usual, and she doesn't know if that means anything or nothing at all.{/i}"
    narrator "I didn't say anything. I didn't say anything. I didn't-"
    narrator "{i}She leaves the hab stack. Behind her, the empty bunk waits for its next occupant. They'll arrive by end of shift. They always do.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Processing Hall. Slurry Line 7. The grinders are louder today, or maybe she's just more aware of them. Every sound feels sharp. Every smell feels deliberate.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She works. Hands moving. Eyes watching. Mind somewhere else.{/i}"
    narrator "Bram. Fifty. The oldest person I've seen here. And the system still stripped his sheets before his body was cold."
    narrator "In five years, I could be the one in the empty bunk. The one they strip the sheets for. The one they call \"burned bright\" and forget."
    narrator "Unless something changes. Unless I find a way out."
    narrator "But the math doesn't allow-"
    narrator "{i}She stops the thought. Pushes it down. Thinking costs. Hoping costs more.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The slurry line pulses. Ore becomes dust. Dust becomes profit. Profit goes somewhere else, to someone else, for reasons that have nothing to do with the people who die making it.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}A supervisor walks past. Not Coil-a different one. He glances at Avyanna's quota display, nods, moves on. She's invisible again. Good.{/i}"
    narrator "Don't be noticed. Don't stand out. Don't be anything except a number."
    narrator "But I noticed Bram. I remember his voice. I know he's gone."
    narrator "That has to mean something. Doesn't it?"
    narrator "{i}It doesn't. It can't. Meaning is a luxury she can't afford.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She keeps working. The grinders keep grinding. The quota keeps climbing. The math keeps running.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Lunch break. Fifteen minutes. The ration pouch tastes like nothing.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna sits against the wall-her wall, the one that lets her watch-and observes the commissary. The patterns of movement. The clusters of workers. The ones who talk and the ones who've stopped trying.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Near the serving line, a foreman is explaining something to a group of younger workers. New arrivals, probably. Their eyes still have hope in them. It won't last.{/i}"
    foreman "{i}[[patient, like he's said this a hundred times]]{/i} The bonus structure is designed to reward productivity. If you exceed quota by fifteen percent, you earn an additional fifty ticks. Twenty percent, seventy-five ticks. The system is fair."
    narrator "{i}Fair. Avyanna almost laughs. Almost.{/i}"
    narrator "The bonus is fifty ticks. The daily interest on average debt is seventy. Even if you hit twenty percent over quota every single day, you still fall behind."
    narrator "But they don't tell the new ones that. They let them figure it out. Let them run the math themselves, if they can. Most can't. Most just work harder and sink faster, thinking they're climbing."
    narrator "{i}One of the new workers raises a hand. Young. Maybe fifteen. Eyes still bright.{/i}"
    new_worker "What if you hit quota every day for a year? Could you pay off your induction debt?"
    narrator "{i}The foreman's smile doesn't waver. But something shifts behind his eyes.{/i}"
    foreman "The system is designed for long-term workers who demonstrate sustained commitment. Early clearance is... uncommon. But not impossible."
    narrator "Not impossible. Just mathematically prevented."
    narrator "{i}The new worker nods, satisfied. They don't see it yet. They will.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna finishes her ration. The paste sits heavy in her stomach. Fuel for the machine. Nothing more.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Afternoon shift. The heat rises. The air thickens. The grinders never stop.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}A worker two stations down-young, thin, coughing-stumbles. Catches himself on the safety rail. Keeps working.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Another worker, three stations up-older, steadier, but slowing-miscounts a measure. Catches the error. Corrects it. The quota display flickers.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The line foreman watches from his elevated platform. His tablet tracks productivity in real-time. Every worker, every minute, every tick.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna watches the foreman. He's been here longer than most. His skin has the gold tint of deep exposure. His lungs probably sound like Vera's-wet, heavy, dying by degrees.{/i}"
    narrator "He's not management. He's one of us, with a slightly better title and slightly worse debt. They promote from within so we have someone to blame who isn't them."
    narrator "{i}The foreman catches her looking. Holds her gaze for a moment. Then looks away.{/i}"
    narrator "He knows. He has to know. He sees the numbers. He runs the same math."
    narrator "But what can he do? Report it? To whom? The system that designed it?"
    narrator "{i}She looks back at her station. The ore keeps coming. The dust keeps settling. The clock keeps running.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}A noise. Different from the grinders.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna looks up. Something is happening near the main corridor-a commotion, voices raised, the sound of bodies moving too fast in a space designed for slow compliance.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Workers are stepping back from their stations. Supervisors are converging. The grinders keep grinding-they always keep grinding-but the humans have stopped.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Someone is on the floor. A worker. Young. Too young. She's convulsing, gold-flecked foam at her mouth, her body arching in a way that isn't natural.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Medical response team arrives. Two attendants with a stretcher. They work fast-not out of urgency, but out of efficiency. The less time the line is disrupted, the better the numbers.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Attendant 1: [[clinical] Toxic reaction. Probably filter failure.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Attendant 2: [[checking vitals] She's crashing. We need to-{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Attendant 1: [[glancing at the line foreman] Can we stabilize on-site?{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The line foreman looks at his tablet. At the numbers. At the girl on the floor.{/i}"
    line_foreman "{i}[[beat]]{/i} Get her to medical. I'll log the incident as \"equipment malfunction.\" Productivity impact: minimal."
    narrator "{i}They carry her away. The convulsing has stopped. Her eyes are open, but there's nothing behind them anymore.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna watches until they're gone. The workers around her are already returning to their stations. The grinders keep grinding. The line keeps moving.{/i}"
    narrator "Equipment malfunction. Not filter failure. Not decades of deferred maintenance. Not a girl who breathed in too much of the dust we all breathe."
    narrator "Equipment malfunction. Because that's a category that doesn't require investigation. Doesn't require change. Doesn't require someone to admit that the equipment is us."
    narrator "{i}Her hands move. The quota climbs. The shift continues.{/i}"
    narrator "Don't think about it. Thinking costs."
    narrator "But she thinks about it anyway."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}End of shift. The siren screams. Avyanna's body releases-not relaxes, never relaxes, just... releases. The difference between working and waiting.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She walks to the hab stack. Her muscles ache. Her lungs feel heavy. The gold dust is in her creases, her pores, her eyelashes. It never comes out completely.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The wash line is long. The water is lukewarm. She scrubs mechanically, watching the gray-gold water swirl down the drain. Her body, dissolving by degrees.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Her tag vibrates. The daily summary.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{b}WORKER 477 - SHIFT SUMMARY{/b}\n{i}Quota:{/i} 351/340 (103%%)\n{i}Base Earnings:{/i} 420 ticks\n{i}Tool Rental:{/i} -90 ticks\n{i}Air Premium:{/i} -60 ticks\n{i}Water Ration:{/i} -30 ticks\n{i}Food Ration:{/i} -45 ticks\n{i}Bunk Rental:{/i} -120 ticks\n{i}Net:{/i} +75 ticks\n{i}Balance Adjustment:{/i} -73 ticks (interest accrual)\n{i}New Balance:{/i} 487,360 ticks (debt)\n{i}Daily Net Change:{/i} +2 ticks{{/color}}"
    narrator "Plus two. I made quota plus thirteen percent. Worked harder than yesterday. And I moved the needle by two ticks."
    narrator "At this rate-two ticks per day-I'll be free in... 667 years."
    narrator "{i}She laughs. It comes out wrong-harsh, broken, the sound of something tearing. The woman next to her glances over, then away. No one asks. Everyone understands.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Night cycle. The viewport.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna stands where she stood before, palms pressed against grimy plastic, eyes fixed on stars she'll never reach.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The mine hums around her. Second shift is working. Third shift is sleeping. The machines never stop. The debt never stops. The dying never stops.{/i}"
    narrator "Do they know? Out there, in the black, do they know about places like this? About people like us?"
    narrator "They must. Someone is buying what we dig. Someone is profiting from what we die for. They know."
    narrator "They just don't care."
    narrator "{i}She traces a constellation with her finger. Three stars in a rough line. She doesn't know its name. She doesn't know any of their names. No one taught her. No one teaches anything here that doesn't make you more productive.{/i}"
    narrator "Out there. Ships move out there. People with choices. People who can leave when they want, go where they want, be who they want."
    narrator "What does that feel like? To not have a number? To not have a balance that only goes up?"
    narrator "{i}Her hand drops. The stars keep burning, indifferent and eternal.{/i}"
    narrator "Bram burned bright. Fifty years, and the system called it acceptable. Called it normal. Called it the cost of doing business."
    narrator "In seven years, will they say that about me? \"Four-seven-seven burned bright. Shame. Good worker.\""
    narrator "Is that all I am? All I'll ever be? A number that worked until it didn't?"
    narrator "{i}Something shifts in her chest. The same weight from before. The same pressure. Like something is waiting, just under the surface.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Her hand goes to the lockbox key around her neck. The stone is in there. The warm stone. She hasn't touched it since that first night, but she can feel it anyway. Waiting.{/i}"
    narrator "What are you? What did you do to me?"
    narrator "Are you why I can't stop thinking? Why I notice things? Why the numbers won't stay quiet in my head?"
    narrator "{i}She doesn't know. She doesn't have answers. She only has questions, and questions cost ticks, and everything costs ticks, and she's so tired of counting.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The corridor is empty. Night cycle deep. The lights are dimmer, the air is colder, and the usual sounds of human habitation have faded to the soft rhythm of sleeping bodies.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna walks. Not toward the hab stack-past it. Toward the observation deck, the one place on the lower levels with a window big enough to see the planet below.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The observation deck is a joke. A leftover from when the mine was built, when someone thought workers might want to look at something other than rock and machinery. The viewport is huge-takes up most of one wall-but it's covered in grime and scratches. The seating has been removed to make space for storage crates.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She doesn't care about the seating. She cares about the view.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The planet hangs below. Brown and gray and orange, wrapped in clouds of industrial haze. Not a living world-a resource world. Extracted, processed, shipped elsewhere. Like her.{/i}"
    narrator "Is that what I am? A resource? Something to be extracted until there's nothing left?"
    narrator "{i}The thought should hurt more than it does. Maybe she's too tired for pain. Maybe she's used it up already.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She sits on a crate. Pulls her knees to her chest. Watches the planet turn, slowly, below the viewport.{/i}"
    narrator "Bram is dead. The girl from the line is probably dead. Tella is dying. Everyone is dying."
    narrator "{i}She thinks about the math again. She can't help it-it runs in her head like a loop, like the grinders, like the debt clock that never stops.{/i}"
    narrator "487,360 ticks. Interest compounding. Rate adjusting. Every day, I fall a little further behind. Every day, the number gets bigger, the hope gets smaller, the exit gets further away."
    narrator "There is no exit. The math doesn't allow it."
    narrator "But what if the math is wrong?"
    narrator "{i}She stops. The thought is strange. Dangerous. Useless.{/i}"
    narrator "The math isn't wrong. The math is the one thing that's honest here. The system shows you exactly how trapped you are."
    narrator "Unless there's something the math doesn't account for. Something outside the system."
    narrator "{i}Her hand goes to the lockbox key again. The stone. The warmth that shouldn't be there.{/i}"
    narrator "Anomalies get reported. Anomalies get investigated. Anomalies get you noticed."
    narrator "But the stone is an anomaly. And I haven't reported it. And nothing has happened. Yet."
    narrator "{i}She looks at the planet below. At the stars beyond. At the vast, indifferent universe that doesn't care whether she lives or dies or burns bright or fades to nothing.{/i}"
    narrator "Something is different. Something has changed."
    narrator "I don't know what. I don't know why. But I can feel it. Like pressure behind my eyes. Like words I can't quite hear."
    narrator "Maybe I'm going mad. Maybe the dust has gotten to my brain, like it's gotten to my lungs."
    narrator "Or maybe-"
    narrator "{i}She stops the thought. Stops all the thoughts. Sits in silence, watching the planet turn, waiting for something she can't name.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}When she finally sleeps, she dreams of numbers.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}They spiral around her-ticks and balances, interest rates and quotas, an endless calculation that never resolves. She's drowning in them, sinking, the weight of mathematics pulling her down into something cold and dark and absolute.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}And somewhere, far away, something watches.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Not the numbers. Not the system. Something older. Something patient. Something that doesn't calculate, doesn't measure, doesn't count.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}It just waits.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}And in the dream, Avyanna reaches toward it-toward the only thing in the dark that isn't made of math.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}She wakes to the siren. Another day. Another count. Another shift.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The numbers are waiting.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}They're always waiting.{/i}"

